      <hedline>
        <hl1>Drinking on Campus</hl1>
      </hedline>
      <abstract>
        <p>Letter from Dennis P Martell, health educator at Michigan State University, says use of diagnosis 'binge drinking' clouds the issue of student drinking problems; says colleges should measure students' blood alcohol concentrations (Oct 3 article)</p>
      </abstract>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Re ''New Tactics on College Drinking'' (front page, Oct. 3):</p>
        <p>At our university, we rejected the term ''binge drinking'' two years ago as an epidemiological measure.</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Re ''New Tactics on College Drinking'' (front page, Oct. 3):</p>
        <p>At our university, we rejected the term ''binge drinking'' two years ago as an epidemiological measure.</p>
        <p>The purpose of diagnosis is to make clear the problem, not cloud it. ''Binge'' as a measurable concept denotes very little and sends mixed messages.</p>
        <p>Colleges should switch to measuring students' blood alcohol concentration as a measure of high-risk drinking.</p>
        <p>It is a measure that is well documented in both medical and legal literature and accounts for weight, gender, quantity of alcohol and frequency and duration of consumption.</p>
        <p>DENNIS P. MARTELL  East Lansing, Mich., Oct. 4, 2000</p>
        <p>The writer is a health educator at Michigan State University.</p>
      </block>
